1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,969
Chapter 8 Make Your Attitudes Your Allies Can you read minds?

2
00:00:07,998 --> 00:00:10,769
Reading minds is easier than you think.

3
00:00:10,879 --> 00:00:17,489
Perhaps you've never thought of it, but you read the minds of other people and they read your mind every day.

4
00:00:18,160 --> 00:00:19,410
How do we do it?

5
00:00:19,519 --> 00:00:23,410
We do it automatically, through attitude appraisals.

6
00:00:23,759 --> 00:00:28,689
Remember the song, You Don't Need to Know the Language to Say You're in Love?

7
00:00:28,878 --> 00:00:31,728
Bing Crosby made it famous some years ago.

8
00:00:32,079 --> 00:00:37,250
There's a whole book full of applied psychology packed into those simple lyrics.

9
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:40,850
You don't need to know the language to say you're in love.

10
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:43,570
Anyone who's ever been in love knows that.

11
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,890
And you don't need to know any language to say I like you,

12
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,449
or I despise you, or I think you're important, or unimportant, or I envy you.

13
00:00:55,119 --> 00:00:58,769
You don't need to know words or to use words to say,

14
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:02,850
I like my job, or I'm bored, or I'm hungry.

15
00:01:03,118 --> 00:01:05,410
People speak without a sound.

16
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:09,330
How we think shows through in how we act.

17
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:12,130
Attitudes are mirrors of the mind.

18
00:01:12,240 --> 00:01:13,890
They reflect thinking.

19
00:01:14,720 --> 00:01:17,728
You can read the mind of the fellow sitting at a desk.

20
00:01:17,840 --> 00:01:23,970
You sense, by observing his expressions and mannerisms, how he feels toward his job.

21
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:28,690
You can read the minds of salesmen, students, husbands, and wives.

22
00:01:28,880 --> 00:01:31,410
You not only can, you do.

23
00:01:32,478 --> 00:01:37,970
The expert actors, those in demand in movies and television year after year,

24
00:01:38,240 --> 00:01:40,609
in a sense are not actors at all.

25
00:01:40,880 --> 00:01:42,770
They don't play their roles.

26
00:01:42,880 --> 00:01:49,089
Instead, they lose their own identity and actually think and feel like the character they are playing.

27
00:01:49,200 --> 00:01:50,368
They've got to.

28
00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:54,210
Else they'd look like phonies and their ratings would plunge.

29
00:01:54,880 --> 00:01:57,330
Attitudes do more than show through.

30
00:01:57,440 --> 00:01:59,330
They sound through, too.

31
00:01:59,759 --> 00:02:06,530
A secretary does more than identify an office when she says, good morning, Mr. Shoemaker's office.

32
00:02:06,798 --> 00:02:11,090
In just five words, one secretary says, I like you.

33
00:02:11,198 --> 00:02:12,769
I'm glad you're calling.

34
00:02:12,879 --> 00:02:14,448
I think you are important.

35
00:02:14,718 --> 00:02:16,289
I like my job.

36
00:02:17,118 --> 00:02:22,689
But another secretary saying exactly the same words tells you, you bothered me.

37
00:02:22,879 --> 00:02:24,370
I wish you hadn't called.

38
00:02:24,399 --> 00:02:28,689
I'm bored with my job and I don't like people who bother me.

39
00:02:29,599 --> 00:02:34,370
We read attitudes through expressions and voice tones and inflections.

